1

00:00:04,740  -->  00:00:07,075
As we saw previously,

2

00:00:07,075  -->  00:00:08,945
when we have two numeric variables,

3

00:00:08,945  -->  00:00:10,644
at least one of them discrete,

4

00:00:10,644  -->  00:00:15,629
jitter and transparency can be used to make the trends in the data clearer.

5

00:00:15,630  -->  00:00:20,039
If we want to plot a quantitative variable against a qualitative variable,

6

00:00:20,039  -->  00:00:21,684
we could take the same approach,

7

00:00:21,684  -->  00:00:26,169
just mapping each level of the qualitative variable to an arbitrary number.

8

00:00:26,170  -->  00:00:31,135
For example, let's say that we have a number of game scores from three different teams,

9

00:00:31,135  -->  00:00:33,820
North, Central, and South.

10

00:00:33,820  -->  00:00:37,424
If we associate one with North, two at Central,

11

00:00:37,424  -->  00:00:40,669
and three with South, then we could use a jittered scatter plot

12

00:00:40,670  -->  00:00:44,780
with team on the x-axis and score on the y-axis.

13

00:00:44,780  -->  00:00:48,219
A more common visualization for this quantitative

14

00:00:48,219  -->  00:00:52,265
versus qualitative comparison is the violin plot.

15

00:00:52,265  -->  00:00:55,265
Instead of plotting data points individually,

16

00:00:55,265  -->  00:00:56,929
we have a curve for each level of

17

00:00:56,929  -->  00:01:01,704
the categorical variable whose area depicts the distribution of points.

18

00:01:01,704  -->  00:01:03,614
Where the curve is wider,

19

00:01:03,615  -->  00:01:05,490
there are more data points.

20

00:01:05,489  -->  00:01:10,750
It's basically a smooth histogram or density curve turned on its side.

21

00:01:10,750  -->  00:01:15,920
For North, you can see that they scored more points in the 50's than the 60's.

22

00:01:15,920  -->  00:01:21,820
You can also see that Central tends to score more points than either North or South.

23

00:01:21,819  -->  00:01:24,489
Compared to the jittered scatter plot,

24

00:01:24,489  -->  00:01:28,030
having the distinct curves makes it easier to remember that the variable is

25

00:01:28,030  -->  00:01:31,879
categorical and easier to compare their distributions.
